comments.body:
`node.compute_hash().finalize()` does a full recursive hash computation (including `memoize_hashes` + RLP encoding) for **every** node during iteration. This is only needed for the diagnostic when validation fails — the happy path pays the cost for nothing.

Consider deferring the hash computation to the error case. You could store the last node itself (or its RLP) and only hash it when building the error:

```rust
let mut last_node: Option<Node> = None;
// ...
for (path, node) in self.into_iter() {
    last_valid_path = Some(path);
    last_node_type = Some(match &node { /* ... */ });
    last_node = Some(node.clone()); // or restructure to avoid clone
    // ...
}
// In error path:
let last_node_hash = last_node.map(|n| n.compute_hash().finalize());
```

Alternatively, just drop the hash from the diagnostic entirely — the path and node type are probably sufficient for debugging, and the hash can be looked up from the path.
